{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_016KWUznGyqQTNbcQ3Unzq1n","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The TOML file still has the correct host. So the file wasn't overwritten. The issue is that nginx needs a full restart (not just a reload) to pick up the new OTel configuration. The nginx OTel module reads the TOML at nginx startup, not at reload.\n\nBut wait - the controller log shows a RELOAD happened after my TOML edit. The `nginx -s reload` sends a SIGHUP which causes nginx master to reload its workers. When new workers start, they should read the TOML again... \nActually, looking at that error message more carefully - it's complaining about an empty hostname in the OTLP endpoint. But the trace IDs in the access logs are non-empty, which means tracing is actually working. So the error must be happening after those initial requests succeeded.\n\nThis points to the exporter being initialized once when nginx starts, and subsequent reloads don't pick up the updated TOML configuration. The TOML was read at the original startup before I patched it, so the host field was empty then. To fix this, I need to do a full restart of the nginx process, not just a reload - either by restarting the controller pod or doing a rolling restart of the deployment.\n\nBut I'm wondering if the controller will rewrite the TOML file from the ConfigMap before nginx starts up. If the ConfigMap has the correct collector host, the TOML should be written correctly. Let me think through whether that's actually happening.\n\nActually, the real issue is that the `opentelemetry-collector-host` ConfigMap key isn't being applied to the TOML at all. So restarting the controller won't help unless I find the correct key or use an alternative approach. I could try using the `OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT` environment variable instead, which the TOML comment mentions as an option. For gRPC, this should be in the format `grpc://host:port` or just `host:port`. Let me try setting this env var on the controller deployment.\n\nWait, actually looking at the OpenTelemetry spec more carefully, for gRPC the endpoint format should be `http://host:port`, not `grpc://`. If I set `OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT=http://otel-collector.otel.svc:4317` on the controller deployment, it should take precedence over the host field in the TOML. But I need to think through the timing here—when the controller starts, it writes the TOML with an empty host, then I manually edit it, but nginx was already running with the old config. I need to restart nginx to pick up the changes.\n\nThe issue is that `nginx -s reload` might not re-read the TOML file if the OTel module only initializes at startup. So I'd need a full nginx restart, which means restarting the controller pod. But that brings me back to the original problem—the controller will write the TOML with an empty host again unless I can fix the ConfigMap key issue or use the environment variable approach instead.\n\nActually, let me reconsider the reload behavior. The nginx master process spawns new workers when reloading, and they should read the updated TOML. The old workers might still be handling connections gracefully, so the OTel errors could be coming from them. I should wait a bit after the reload and test again to see if the new workers are actually using the correct configuration.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":563,"cache_read_input_tokens":49844,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":563},"output_tokens":21,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6900e73d-14d0-4d14-bd90-3db0c1439efe","uuid":"64e04bae-f80f-436f-8c69-6215a84e89ea","request_id":"req_011CcMTMxjE82nD1A3N4Pn2h"}
